main event: A series of 14 photographs were taken in Glen Burnie, Maryland on August 17, 1949. The photographs depict various parts of a circular disc-like object and an aircraft fuselage, some of which are mounted on a tripod or stand. Additionally, there is a photograph showing wreckage or debris scattered across a flat surface along with a clearly defined section referred to as a 'fuselage and cockpit.'
interesting points: The photographs are partially obscured with white paper strips, likely to hide certain details.

The topmost photograph shows a tail assembly and part of a disc, the middle one displays what seems to be a fuselage with a cockpit, and the bottom photograph shows a disc-like object with a tripod mounting and brake drum nearby.
One of the photographs depicts an area primarily in darkness with a notable structure in the foreground, described as a 'fuselage and cockpit.'
The background of one photograph shows an overexposed section of light, and possibly wooden beams or framework are barely discernible in the darkness.
Another image shows an aircraft that is partially dismantled or damaged, resting on the ground with a building in the background, as well as a close-up view of an aircraft's rotor plane.
sighted object: various parts of a circular disc-like object and an aircraft fuselage
